---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const seo = {
  title: "Loading Group of Products | Anna Kocaj",
  description:
    "Research-driven redesign of the Vendos machine loading flow — and the decision not to ship the bigger redesign once testing showed the trade-off.",
  image: "/loading_workshops.png",
};
---

<Layout seo={seo}>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="mt-10 max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6">
    <a
      href="/projects"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 opacity-50 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity text-sm mb-8"
    >
      ← Back to projects
    </a>

    <p class="text-sm opacity-50 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3 font-medium">
      Case Study · 2025
    </p>
    <h1 class="font-bold text-3xl mb-4 leading-snug">
      Loading Products Research
    </h1>
    <p class="text-lg opacity-70 mb-8 max-w-xl leading-relaxed">
      A redesign that made loading easier for first-time storekeepers, but also
      made it slower for experienced ones.
    </p>

    <!-- Overview grid -->
    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-4 py-6 border-t border-b border-white/10 mb-10"
    >
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">My Role</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">Product Designer</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">Tools</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">Figma, Miro</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero image -->
    <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
      <Image
        src="/loading_workshops.png"
        alt="Zoom out on Miro Board"
        width={1200}
        height={675}
        class="w-full object-cover"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHALLENGE -->
  <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-4">The Challenge</h2>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Vendos machines are loaded by storekeepers with health & safety products.
      Our business strategy set a hard requirement: clients should never need
      training to use the product, so distribution stays uninterrupted and their
      staff's time stays free for other work.
    </p>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed">
      We didn't actually know whether the current loading flow met that bar. The
      research question was simple and specific: <strong
        >can someone load the machine correctly with zero training?</strong
      >
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- PROCESS -->
  <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-8">Process</h2>

    <div class="space-y-12">
      <!-- Step 1 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          01 — Research
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">
          Watching people load a machine they've never seen
        </h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          I designed and led task-based usability sessions. Participants has
          never used the product before, simulating a real first day on the job.
          Each was handed a QR code and a key and asked to play the role of a
          new storekeeper: load 5 gloves into the machine, then log out.
          Follow-up questions stayed neutral: what surprised you, what did you
          expect to happen, how would you explain this to someone else. A
          teammate observed each session, tracking reactions and friction
          points, with a short debrief after every participant.
        </p>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm">
          The findings clustered into three groups: missing feedback, unclear
          guidance, and physical friction. The pattern across all of it: <strong
            >the loading task itself was simple, the real problem was the
            first-time experience.</strong
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 2 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          02 — Concept
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">
          Designing for someone who's never seen this machine
        </h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          I redesigned loading flow that addressed the research findings
          directly: confirmation after every action, an explicit "finish
          loading" step, precise cell-range guidance instead of a misleading
          range and short contextual prompts guiding each physical step.
        </p>
        <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
          <Image
            src="/loading_mockups.png"
            alt="Redesigned beginner-focused loading flow"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="w-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 3 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          03 — Validate & Decide
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">
          Better for newcomers, worse for the everyday case
        </h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          When we tested the redesign, it worked as intended for first-time
          users, but it also made the process noticeably longer for experienced
          storekeepers who already knew what they were doing. That mattered:
          Vendos machines aren't loaded once, they're loaded by the same people,
          repeatedly, as part of their regular job. Optimizing purely for a
          first-time experience would have made the everyday case worse for the
          people who use the machine most. Rather than ship a design that traded
          one user's efficiency for another's, we made the call not to ship the
          full redesign. Instead, we shipped smaller fixes from the research
          without adding any extra steps to the flow experienced storekeepers
          already knew.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm">
        The research also reframed the problem itself: since the loading task is
        fundamentally simple, first-time friction is better solved outside the
        loading screen, through onboarding, not by adding weight to a flow that
        thousands repeat every day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- NAVIGATION -->
  <section
    class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16 flex justify-center items-center border-t border-white/10 pt-8"
  >
    <a
      href="/projects"
      class="opacity-50 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity text-sm"
    >
      ← All projects
    </a>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  strong {
    color: white;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  em {
    color: inherit;
  }
</style>
